properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls will continue into this afternoon. The most intense snow squall currently is located from Pickerel River extending northeastwards to areas north of city North Bay. Under the most intense snow squall bands snow accumulation can be up to 15 cm . Conditions should improve this evening after a cold front pass. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River from St. Jean Baptiste through the City of Winnipeg (except for Ste. Agathe) due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A cold and snowy start to the week. A low pressure system over the Northeastern United States will bring snow to Southern and Central Quebec beginning Monday evening. The snow will continue through Tuesday, reaching Eastern Quebec. The morning commute will be difficult on Tuesday for the Greater Montreal area. The snow will be accompanied by moderate winds possibly reducing visibilities. Close to 10 centimetres of snow are expected over Southern and Central Quebec by Tuesday evening, while higher snowfall amounts are possible over the Appalachians area. The system will intensify and continue to affect Eastern Quebec on Wednesday, with snow, strong winds and blowing snow expected. Snow will gradually change to rain over the Lower North Shore. Quickly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Hazardous travelling conditions can be expected due to changing visibilities possibly going from good to zero. The public is advised to monitor future forecasts for more information as the low pressure system's track becomes more certain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-10T12:55:37-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential significant snowfall on Monday A developing system tracking south of the Lower Great Lakes will bring snow into portions of southern Ontario Sunday night into Monday. Due to lake enhancement, areas near the Niagara region have the potential to receive near 10 to 15 cm snow by Monday evening. There is still considerable uncertainty with regards to the track of this system thus the northern edge of significant snow. Travel may be impacted Monday due to the snow accumulation on the road. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight into Sunday. Snow squalls are expected to develop off Lake Nipigon tonight behind a strong cold front and persist through Sunday. There is a possibility that the squalls will continue through Monday as well as winds are expected to remain out of the north or northwest. Localized accumulations of 15 to 25 cm are possible by Sunday evening with additional snowfall possible on Monday. Travel conditions along Highway 11 could be particularly hazardous. Motorists are advised to watch for quickly changing weather conditions and adjust their driving accordingly. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow and gusty winds will continue along parts of Highway 97 late this afternoon and taper off to a few flurries late this evening. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of freezing drizzle are expected or occurring. Patch freezing drizzle is expected this evening. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing drizzle advisories are issued when drizzle falling in sub-zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Heavy snow will begin this evening over southern Alberta, with total accumulations expected to range between 10-20 cm by Sunday afternoon. For areas along the foothills or near the Cypress Hills, total accumulations could reach 25 cm. Temperatures are also expected to fall on Sunday as skies clear and the ridge builds in from the north. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
